summary.seg: This manuscript contains the five Leuctran orations by Aelius Aristides (orr. 11-15 Lenz-Behr). Aristides (b. ca. 118, d. ca. 181 CE), was a Greek rhetor and a leading exponent of the Second Sophistic, a philosophical-literary current developed in Asia Minor during the imperial age, between the end of the 1st and the 4th century CE. The five Leuctran orations represent the imagined debate in the Athenian Assembly over which side to support after Thebes beat Sparta in the Battle of Leuctra in 371 BCE, and invited Athens to participate in further campaigns.

The manuscript was copied between the end of the 15th century and the beginning of the 16th century, and was initially owned by the Byzantine scholar Janus Lascaris (b. 1445?, d. 1535). After the Fall of Constantinople (1453), Lascaris moved to Italy under the protection of Cardinal Bessarion. After the death of the Cardinal, he entered the service of Lorenzo de' Medici in Florence, who sent him to Greece in search of manuscripts. Later on, he was the ambassador of France in Venice, where he became a member of the Greek Academy of Aldus Manutius. He also assisted the French king Louis XII in forming the library of Blois.
Matthaeus Devaris (b. 1505, d. 1581), a student of Lascaris, added a pinax, an index of the manuscript.
A hypothesis introduces the texts; spaces were left for the titles and the first letters of each oration but these were never completed.

support.material: Western paper, folded in 32mo, sheet size 105 70 Watermark: Balance ( 90-100 45 ) near the fore-edge comparable to Briquet, 2578-2584, and Harlfinger Balance 65-71.

supportDesc.foliation: [i] + 1-87. Foliated in pencil in Arabic numerals in the upper right-hand corner, recto.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 11 quaternions, the last of which is missing a folio.
collation.signatures: Quire signatures: brown ink quire marks in Greek numerals from βον (f. 9r) to ιον (f. 73r) in the bottom right of the first folio, recto of the quire, original to the production of the volume.

supportDesc.condition: In good condition; occasional humidity and water stains (e.g. ff. [i] recto, 18-21, 28-36). There are two wormholes (ff. [i]-19 and 78-87) of2 mm diameter and occasional brown stains (e.g. f. 50r).

layoutDesc.layout:
Written space 75 50
Main text: 16 lines per page. On ff. 1r, 47r, 57v, 68r titles are missing and one line is blank; two lines on f. 23r.

handNote.p: The main text is written in a small minuscule of the end of the 15th century or the beginning of the 16th century. Slanted to the right, the hand uses several majuscule letters (β, γ, η, λ, π) and ligatures. Presence of modern ny and sigma telikon, and both high and low gamma and tau. Breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or breathings.

binding.p: 18th-century board binding covered in quarter mid-brown tanned calfskin with blue-green paper on the sides, not contemporary with the text. 110 83 21

provenance.p: The manuscript belonged initially to the library of the Byzantine scholar Janus Lascaris Lascaris, Janus, 1445?-1535 (b. 1445?, d. 1535), as testified by his cipher in f. [i] recto (a large kappa whose upper portion of the left vertical stroke serves also for the right half of an appended lambda, and whose bottom part of the vertical stroke has a sigma to the left and a rho to the right; see: Jackson 2003).

Later on, this manuscript entered in the library of the Cardinal
Niccolò Ridolfi Ridolfi, Niccolò, 1501-1550 (b. 1501, d. 1550); Ridolfi's designation is preserved on [i] recto: nº 55 della decimae (sic) (the last two words written over a struck-out della 21 ).

The volume was part of the queen of France Catherine de Médici Catherine de Médicis, Queen, consort of Henry II, King of France, 1519-1589 's estate in 1589 (Muratore, La biblioteca). It seems to have been removed from the French Royal collection before 1622 by Jean-Baptiste Hautin Haultin, Jean-Baptiste, approximately 1580-1640 (b. 1580?, d. 1640), who probably added the ex libris on the pastedown, and an erroneous description Aristidis orationes et alia . It later passed into the collection of John Moore Moore, John, 1646-1714 (b. 1646, d. 1714), bishop of Ely; but the manuscript is not sorted in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) nor in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner after the publication of Bernard's catalogue.

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . The royal bookplate engraved by John Pine (1690-1756) in 1736 remains.
